Caption:
FILE – In this Jan. 31, 2014 photo, David Pecker, Chairman and CEO of American Media, addresses those attending the Shape & Men’s Fitness Super Bowl Party in New York.  The National Enquirer kept a safe containing documents on hush-money payments and other damaging stories it killed as part of its cozy relationship with Donald Trump leading up to 2016 presidential election, people familiar with the arrangement told The Associated Press.

Date: PUBLISHED: February 10, 2019 at 5:00 am | UPDATED: February 11, 2019 at 8:14 am
Caption: Cindy Lannon holds a picture of her deceased husband, Jerry Lannon, in Stillwater on Wednesday, Jan. 9, 2019. Lannon, 58, a deputy with the Washington County Sheriff’s Office who was diagnosed with depression and PTSD, committed suicide the Monday after Thanksgiving last year. (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)

Cindy Lannon talks about her late husband, Jerry Lannon, 58, a deputy with the Washington County sheriff’s office. “He has just a really strong faith and he loved studying God’s word. He loved history too,” Lannon said. “I felt that the day Jerry died some of his integrity was tarnished. He didn’t want his life to end that way.” (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)

“Everywhere I look there are badges around,” said Cindy Lannon, who keeps a collection of badges from her late husband, Jerry Lannon, under a photo of her daughters in her home. Lannon is working to raise awareness about officer suicides and mental illness, including depression and post-traumatic stress disorder. (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)
Cindy Lannon shows photos of her and her late husband, Jerry Lannon, on Wednesday, Jan. 9, 2019. On the right is their wedding picture in Hawaii from Jan. 7, 2002. (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)

Cindy Lannon shows a photo of her late husband, Jerry Lannon, at his parents’ burial site in Savage. Lannon, who died by suicide the Monday after Thanksgiving last year, was buried near where he is standing. (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)

Cindy Lannon wants to write a book about her husband’s life — and death. ‘I’m going to call it ‘The Thin Blue Line,’ and then cross out ‘Thin’ and write ‘Broken,’ ” she said. (Jean Pieri / Pioneer Press)

Lindsey Vonn is planning to “take on the world” after retiring from skiing after the world championships in Sweden. That is set to include becoming a businesswoman, getting into the movie industry _ both behind and in front of the camera _ and becoming a mother. She says one of the reasons she is calling an end to her sports career now is so she doesn’t damage her body even more, to the extent that she wouldn’t be able to go skiing with her own children.2019. (AP Photo/Richard Drew, File)

That is set to include becoming a businesswoman, getting into the movie industry _ both behind and in front of the camera _ and becoming a mother. She says one of the reasons she is calling an end to her sports career now is so she doesn’t damage her body even more, to the extent that she wouldn’t be able to go skiing with her own children.2019. “I’m a driven person,” said Vonn, who has 1.6 million Instagram followers and, at the height of her career in 2013, was worth $3 million according to Forbes. “I’m not going to be sitting on the couch, twiddling my thumbs. Caption: Ros Remlinger, who has worked at the loading dock at the airport said, if you're going to be outside, dress in layers. But above all, don't forget the Under Armor, Carhartts and -60 Muck boots! (Courtesy of Ros Remlinger Jan. 29, 2019)
Penny Nelson said her favorite winter gear is her Love My Melon Golden Gopher hat. "So warm and cozy!" (Courtesy of Penny Nelson Jan. 29, 2019)
Cassi Brand said for her three-year-old daughter Kylie, "Dads gloves get the job done."
For Katherine Tilly of Farmington, it's not as much about warmth as it is about survival. She likes this hat "because I survived the Blizzard of ‘91 and I’ll survive this one too!"

Elliot Williams loves his Muck boots that are rated for -60 "because it’s Minnesota" and his bibs "because I get the comfort of wearing my sweatpants underneath," he said. He also swears by his high visibility jacket and sweatshirt "so others can see me on the lake or while working! Safety first! And because ice fishing is life!" (Courtesy of Elliot Williams Jan. 29, 2019)
Whether hunting rabbit, duck or a good spot for ice fishing, Doug Erickson of Farmington goes with the ole Elmer Fudd hat "so his ears don't fall off." (Courtesy of Susan Erickson Jan. 29, 2019)

It's all about keeping the head and face covered for Elizabeth Jensen and her son Merrick in Mounds View. "My favorite is my Buff brand neck/face warmer because it keeps the worst of the cold off my face and can still breathe through it in the cold. My son’s is his puffy ball hat because it keeps his head nice and toasty. " (Courtesy of Elizabeth Jensen Jan. 29, 2019)
Melissa Davis from White Bear Lake kept her puppy warm. Memphis the dog says, "My favorite winter gear is my scarf. Because sweaters are for wimps." (Courtesy of Melissa Davis Jan. 29, 2019)

Toni Shearer knows being warm is better than being fashionable.
"I asked for this snowsuit for Christmas and my family laughed!! Who’s laughing now? I’m warm!!!!" (Courtesy of Toni Shearer Jan. 29, 2019)

Hunters know what it takes to keep warm. David Bigler
describes his winter gear as "four layers of thermals, warm socks, boots, hat and gloves are a must sitting outside for periods of time, protecting people's animals from predators."
